04433nam a22005415i 9780822392217DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223922177 a10.1515/97808223922172doi  a(DE-B1597)554510  a(OCoLC)1086431969  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1993.5.I8b.S27 2009 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43658354042231 aSarkar, Bhaskar, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMourning the Nation :bIndian Cinema in the Wake of Partition /cBhaskar Sarkar. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b63 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: National Cinema's Hermeneutic of Mourning -- tPart I. A Resonant Silence -- t1. Cinema's Project of Nationhood -- t2. Runes of Laceration -- t3. Bengali Cinema: A Spectral Subnationality -- tPart II. The Return of the Repressed -- t4. Dispersed Nodes of Articulation -- t5. Ghatak, Melodrama, and the Restitution of Experience -- t6. Tamas and the Limits of Representation -- t7. Mourning (Un)limited -- tCoda: The Critical Enchantment of Mourning -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat remains of the "national" when the nation unravels at the birth of the independent state? The political truncation of India at the end of British colonial rule in 1947 led to a social cataclysm in which roughly one million people died and ten to twelve million were displaced. Combining film studies, trauma theory, and South Asian cultural history, Bhaskar Sarkar follows the shifting traces of this event in Indian cinema over the next six decades. He argues that Partition remains a wound in the collective psyche of South Asia and that its representation on screen enables forms of historical engagement that are largely opaque to standard historiography.Sarkar tracks the initial reticence to engage with the trauma of 1947 and the subsequent emergence of a strong Partition discourse, revealing both the silence and the eventual "return of the repressed" as strands of one complex process. Connecting the relative silence of the early decades after Partition to a project of postcolonial nation-building and to trauma's disjunctive temporal structure, Sarkar develops an allegorical reading of the silence as a form of mourning. He relates the proliferation of explicit Partition narratives in films made since the mid-1980s to disillusionment with post-independence achievements, and he discusses how current cinematic memorializations of 1947 are influenced by economic liberalization and the rise of a Hindu-chauvinist nationalism. Traversing Hindi and Bengali commercial cinema, art cinema, and television, Sarkar provides a history of Indian cinema that interrogates the national (a central category organizing cinema studies) and participates in a wider process of mourning the modernist promises of the nation form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aMotion pictureszIndia. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392217zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392217423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392217.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles